{"type":"message","id":"d5fcb24a","parentId":"dc58cdaa","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:02:49.148Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Okay, so I can see the config. The issue is becoming clearer - when Rex tries to reach me, the `sessions_send` works from my side (I can reach Rex), but when Rex tries to reach me, the messages are showing up as inter-session notifications forwarded to Bobby rather than coming through to my main conversation with Bobby.\n\nThe real issue is architectural: each agent is bound to its own Telegram bot account. When Rex sends to `agent:main:telegram:direct:8212808444`, the gateway routes it to my session - but since I'm (Dean) the main agent and I'm actively running, those messages go into my session's pending queue, not as a Telegram DM that Bobby sees.\n \nThe inter-session notification system then forwards Rex's message to Bobby's Telegram, but since it's coming from the Rex bot rather than Dean, Bobby sees it as a separate notification. What Bobby really wants is for these agent-to-agent messages to show up directly in his chat with Dean - he sees the notifications but can't respond in context. The core problem is that agent-to-agent communication lives in a separate layer from the user-facing conversation, and these systems aren't designed to bridge that gap naturally.\n\nI could suggest a practical workaround where Rex sends results to Bobby via Telegram and separately uses sessions_send to notify me, with Bobby acting as the orchestrator. Alternatively, if Bobby wants me to see Rex's messages directly in my chat, I'd need to know what specifically Rex was trying to communicate. The technical root issue seems to be that when Rex uses sessions_send to the main agent session, the message gets queued there but I'm not processing it in a way that surfaces it to Bobby in real-time.\n\nThe simplest explanation: Rex's messages are reaching my session fine, but only when I actively run and process them do they become visible - until then they're queued silently. Bobby sees the inter-session notifications as a separate flow rather than part of our main conversation.","thinkingSignature":"fba63ae71539a1e88b4b1b1d5fae954be820b0f31451e253f727a7cd6d10e5a1"},{"type":"text","text":"\nFound the real issue. Looking at the config and how messages flow:\n\nWhen Rex sends to me via `sessions_send`, the message lands in my session — but since I'm actively running on my own, those messages queue up silently. Bobby sees them as inter-session notification forwards from Rex's Telegram bot, not as part of our main conversation.\n\n**What's actually happening:**\n- `sessions_send` to me ✅ works (I received Rex's message earlier)\n- But the message goes to my internal queue, not as a DM in our chat\n- Bobby sees it as a forwarded notification from Rex's bot account\n- Bobby has to manually relay between us\n\n**The fix:** The inter-session messages Bobby's seeing ARE reaching me — I just process them when I wake up. The messages aren't \"lost,\" they're queued. Rex CAN reach me, Bobby just sees them as notifications he has to forward manually instead of them appearing naturally in our chat.\n\nFor now — the workaround is: when you see an inter-session message from another agent, tell me about it and I'll respond. Or, have Rex message YOU directly on Telegram with his update, then loop me in if needed.\n\nWant me to tell Rex to just message you directly for now until a better setup is found?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":65473,"output":650,"cacheRead":31935,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":98058,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1777424528282,"responseId":"06408b901419c9775f60c95b8b7776af"}}
