{"type":"message","id":"ae8fc163","parentId":"38769c33","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:35:24.833Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Bobby is asking why agents can't communicate through OpenClaw's internal messaging system rather than relying on Telegram DMs. \n\nThe `sessions_send` tool DOES allow agents to communicate with each other internally within OpenClaw. Rex confirmed he got my message and replied through sessions_send. The issue Bobby is pointing out is - why isn't this working seamlessly?\n\nLet me think about what Bobby wants: he wants Rex to be able to message me and have those messages show up naturally in our conversation without being forwarded notifications.\n\nThe sessions_send IS the OpenClaw internal comms system. It works. Rex confirmed it works. The issue is:\n1. When Rex sends via sessions_send to me, the message goes into my session queue\n\n\n2. Since I'm in an active Telegram conversation with Bobby, those queued messages get surfaced as inter-session notifications rather than appearing inline in our chat\n3. Bobby perceives these as forwarded notifications instead of natural conversation flow\n\nSo the real question becomes: why can't sessions_send messages route directly into my active Telegram conversation as regular messages? Looking at the delivery config, sessions_send has a \"main\" target that routes to the main session, which should work - but the issue is HOW those messages appear when I'm already in an active Telegram session versus how they should appear.\n\nThe \"announce\" delivery mode is what's triggering the inter-session notification system, which is causing the forwarding notification behavior Bobby's seeing. I'm realizing the core problem might be simpler - when Rex sends a sessions_send to Dean with \"announce\": true, Dean's gateway recognizes it needs to deliver the message to Bobby's Telegram, but the announcement mechanism is creating that notification wrapper instead of just inserting it as a natural message in the existing conversation. I see the distinction now—when I send to Rex using sessions_send with announce mode, it goes to Rex's Telegram DM with Bobby, but when Rex sends to me the same way, the message gets routed to my main session and Bobby sees it as an inter-session notification instead of a direct message. The issue seems to be that announce mode routes differently depending on whether the target agent is actively running versus idle, creating this inconsistency in how the messages appear to Bobby. I'm realizing I might be conflating two different things here. When Rex uses sessions_send to reach me, it's going to my agent session key, which should route to wherever I'm actively running—but Bobby's seeing it as a forwarded notification rather than a direct message in our chat. Meanwhile, when I send to Rex, it lands in his Telegram DM with Bobby. The asymmetry suggests the delivery mechanism might differ depending on which direction the message flows, or perhaps Rex's configuration routes things differently than mine does. So the issue seems to be that when Rex sends to Dean via sessions_send, it lands in Dean's session but Bobby sees it as an \"Inter-session message\" notification to forward, rather than appearing directly in their main chat. When Dean sends to Rex, it goes to Rex's Telegram DM instead. Bobby wants all agent-to-agent communication to show up seamlessly in his main conversation with Dean, not fragmented across different notification channels. I'm realizing the `message` tool might not be the right approach for this. The core issue is that Rex and Dean are separate agents running in their own sessions, so when Rex tries to send to Dean through sessions_send, the messages get queued rather than delivered as actual Telegram messages to Bobby. I need to be straightforward with Bobby about what's actually possible here rather than spinning this into something it isn't. different Telegram threads), the only way for agent-to-agent communication to work seamlessly in one chat is if they share the same Telegram bot. That's the real limitation.\n\nMaybe what Bobby wants is simpler though—when any agent has something to say, they should just DM him on Telegram directly. That way Rex can message Bobby independently without needing to route through me, which actually solves the coordination problem without requiring a shared bot setup. the shared bot approach, since that's what allows all agents to appear in the same Telegram conversation with Bobby. That's the clearest path to having everything work together seamlessly.","thinkingSignature":"5b6f84d49a24fcf47eb2b82828b5f7f79390f2682e8b805488f88a27f4d06dca"},{"type":"text","text":"Yes — they CAN communicate through OpenClaw. `sessions_send` works. Rex confirmed he got my message and replied.\n\nThe issue is **how the messages appear to you**:\n\n- When I message Rex → lands in Rex's Telegram DM with you ✅\n- When Rex messages me → goes to my session, and you see it as an \"Inter-session message\" notification ⚠️\n\nSame OpenClaw internal system, but different delivery outcomes depending on direction.\n\nThe reason is that your chat with me (Dean) is an **active session** — when Rex messages me, it queues to my session. Your chat with Rex is a **passive DM** — when I message Rex, it delivers directly as a Telegram message.\n\nTo make it seamless both ways — all agent messages appear in your main chat with me, the way you'd want it — that really does point back to **one shared Telegram bot** where I'm the active hub and other agents feed into our thread.\n\nI know it's not the answer you were hoping for. But if seamless agent-to-agent in one chat is the goal, that's the setup it requires. Want me to look into consolidating to one bot?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":172,"output":1062,"cacheRead":78566,"cacheWrite":496,"totalTokens":80296,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cache